<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[192,1440,1370,1618]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,527,1370,1394]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis and remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nearns &amp; Monné" authorityYear="2019" box="[538,795,1370,1394]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Neocherentes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pergeri">
<emphasis box="[538,795,1370,1394]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Neocherentes pergeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can easily be separated from its congeners by the metasternum and abdominal ventrites with mottled whitish-grey coloration (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1168,1350,1402,1426]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Neocherentes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilloniorum">
<emphasis box="[1168,1350,1402,1426]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">N. dilloniorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nearns &amp; Monné" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Neocherentes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adrianoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">N. adrianoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the metasternum and abdominal ventrites continue the distinct pattern found on the elytra (
<figureCitation box="[201,305,1466,1490]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[192,275,1587,1609]" captionTargetBox="[336,1296,213,1553]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[336,1296,213,1553]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Three species of Neocherentes Tippmann, 1960, holotype specimens. a) N. dilloniorum, lateral view. b) N. adrianoi, lateral view. c) N. pergeri, lateral view. d) N. dilloniorum, close-up of abdominal ventrites. e) N. adrianoi, close-up of abdominal ventrites. f) N. pergeri, close-up of abdominal ventrites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3673168" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3673168/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 4c, f</figureCitation>
)). This species is known from four specimens (one male, three females) collected in pre-Andean Chiquitano transition forest in 
<collectingRegion box="[573,865,1498,1522]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Santa Cruz de la Sierra</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[877,963,1498,1522]" name="Bolivia" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
at approximately 
<quantity box="[1187,1262,1498,1522]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" unit="m" value="480.0">480 m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[1277,1348,1498,1522]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[192,275,1211,1233]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1177]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[192,1440,213,1177]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 5. Partial map of South America showing the approximate distribution of three species of Neocherentes Tippmann, 1960. Neocherentes dilloniorum (red squares), Neocherentes adrianoi sp. nov. (magenta diamonds), Neocherentes pergeri sp. nov. (blue circles)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3673170" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3673170/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Nothing is known about the biology of this species. The 
<typeStatus box="[811,909,1530,1554]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">allotype</typeStatus>
male of this species was recently figured in a beautifully illustrated photographic guide to longhorned beetles of 
<collectingCountry box="[1024,1110,1562,1586]" name="Bolivia" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lingafelter, S. W. &amp; J. E. Wappes &amp; J. Ledezma Arias" box="[1153,1440,1562,1586]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" refId="ref5085" refString="Lingafelter, S. W., J. E. Wappes, and J. Ledezma Arias. 2017. Photographic guide to longhorned beetles of Bolivia. Smithsonian Institution Scholarly Press; Washington, DC. 260 p." type="book" year="2017">Lingafelter et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[226,409,1594,1618]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Neocherentes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilloniorum">
<emphasis box="[226,409,1594,1618]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">N. dilloniorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
